oets near the start of their careers (such as Brandon Som), and by others who are not—or not yet—well known. The Poem Is You will appeal to poets, teachers, and students, but it is intended especially for readers who want to learn more about contemporary American poetry but who have not known where or how to start. It describes what American poets have fashioned for one another, and what they can give us today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh1 aAlcalá, Rosa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlexander, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAli, Agha Shahid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmmons, A. R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArmantrout, Rae, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAshbery, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBang, Mary Jo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBess, Gabby, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBidart, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrock-Broido, Lucie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClary, Killarney, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClifton, Lucille, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCreeley, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDennis, Carl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDove, Rita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Kari, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEstes, Angie, 